<DOC><DOCNO> AP900905-0220 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-90 1447EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BAT     09-05 0244</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Earns-BAT,0256</SECOND><HEAD>BAT Industries Reports First-Half Earnings</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   BAT Industries PLC, a tobacco and financialservices conglomerate, on Wednesday reported a 17 percent increasein net profits in the first half of the year.   The increase, however, came on an extraordinary gain, and thecompany's pre-tax profit was down 11 percent from the same period ayear ago.   BAT said net profit for the six months ended June 30 came to 773million pounds, or $1.47 billion, compared to 660 million pounds,or $1.25 billion, in the previous six months.   Earnings per share fell 20 percent, to 20.7 pence (39 cents)from 25.5 pence (48.5 cents) a year earlier.   Pre-tax profit was 592 million pounds ($1.125 billion) comparedto 668 million pounds ($1.27 billion).   Sales rose 12 percent to 9.49 billion pounds ($18.03 billion),compared to 8.48 billion pounds ($16.11 billion) in theyear-earlier period.   The earnings report included 468 million pounds in extraordinarygains, largely from BAT's restructuring program. The programincluded the disposal of assets and spinoff of Wiggins TeapeAppleton, a paper and pulp manufacturer, and the Argos retail chain.   A year earlier the group had an extraordinary gain of 270million pounds. ``I am pleased with the growth trends in both ourtobacco and financial services activities,'' said BAT ChairmanPatrick Sheehy. However, he said, the weakness of the dollar anddeclines in world stock markets could affect earnings from thecompany's core businesses for the year.</TEXT></DOC>